just_use main.go

# label: TOOL
# role: DSL → native test code / fixtures generator

Compiles `games/lynrummy/conformance/scenarios/*.dsl` into four
artifacts, each filtered by an `OpKind` row in the registry at
the top of `main.go`:

- **Go** (`games/lynrummy/referee_conformance_test.go`, package
  `lynrummy`) — referee ops only: `validate_game_move`,
  `validate_turn_complete`.
- **Elm** (`games/lynrummy/elm/tests/Game/DslConformanceTest.elm`)
  — every op (Elm is the target-of-record).
- **JSON fixtures** (`games/lynrummy/python/conformance_fixtures.json`)
  — hint/planner ops for the Python runner. Python is interpreted
  so there is no Python codegen; the runner reads the JSON at
  runtime.
- **Ops manifest** (`games/lynrummy/python/conformance_ops.json`)
  — sibling JSON listing the op names each target should run.
  The Python runner reads this at startup and aborts if its
  `DISPATCH` dict diverges from the registry.

Pipeline: parse → AST → registry validate → render templates +
JSON encode → write → go build verify → idempotence check. Same
codegen philosophy as crudgen: the DSL is the source of truth;
all four outputs are build artifacts.

## Adding a new op kind

See `ADDING_AN_OP.md`. Recipe is one registry row + one Elm
emitter + one Python runner; registry-validation and
manifest-cross-check turn forgotten-edit bugs into loud errors
at fixturegen-time and Python-startup-time respectively.

## Supported scenario ops

- `validate_game_move` / `validate_turn_complete` — referee
  (Go + Elm).
- `build_suggestions` — hint.buildSuggestions result rows
  (Elm + Python).
- `hint_invariant` — apply named trick's first play to the
  board, assert every resulting stack classifies cleanly
  (Elm + Python).
- `enumerate_moves` — given a 4-bucket state
  (helper / trouble / growing / complete), assert against
  any combination of:
    - `expect.yields: <type>` — at least one yielded move
      has this type. Cross-language live (Python + Elm).
    - `expect.narrate_contains: <substr>` — at least one
      yielded move's `narrate(desc)` (Steve-facing
      evocative form) contains the substring. Python-only
      today; Elm stub.
    - `expect.hint_contains: <substr>` — at least one
      yielded move's `hint(desc)` (player-facing vague
      nudge) contains the substring. Python-only today;
      Elm stub.
  Successor to the trick-invariant scenarios as those retire.
- `solve` — full BFS planner invocation. `expect: no_plan`
  or `expect.plan_length: N`. Live on both Python and Elm.
- `trick_first_play` — legacy; Elm still honors it, Go no
  longer has tricks.

Routing now lives in the `opRegistry` slice (one row per op,
with Go/Elm/Python target booleans + per-target emitter funcs).
Replaces the older `goSupportedOps` / `pythonSupportedOps` maps
+ Elm switch-default-pass branches; one source of truth and one
recipe to extend (see `ADDING_AN_OP.md`).

## Idiom

Exported AST field names are load-bearing: `text/template` can
only read exported identifiers. Renaming without updating
templates produces silent empty sections.

Build-gate: `go build` runs against the generated file
immediately after emission. Idempotence check: regen and
byte-compare to the just-written bytes. Both fail fast.

## TODO

- No runtime-gate for the Python JSON fixtures: `py_compile`
  against `test_dsl_conformance.py` would catch generator
  schema drift. Low priority — `ops/check` runs the Python
  runner itself so schema drift surfaces as a runtime error,
  and the ops-manifest cross-check now catches op-level drift
  at Python startup.

